{{Speciesbox | image =Castilla_elastica_-_Köhler–s_Medizinal-Pflanzen-174.jpg | genus = Castilla | species = elastica | authority = Cerv. | synonyms = *''Castilla elastica var. liga'' <small>J.Poiss. </small> *''Castilla guatemalensis '' <small>Pittier </small> *''Castilla gummifera'' <small> (Bertol.) Standl. </small> *''Castilla lactiflua'' <small> O.F.Cook </small> *''Castilla markhamiana'' <small> Markham </small> *''Castilla nicoyensis'' <small> O.F.Cook </small> *''Ficus gummifera'' <small> Bertol. </small> *''Urostigma gummiferum'' <small> Miq. </small><ref>http://www.theplantlist.org/tpl/record/kew-2704813</ref> }}
'''''Castilla elastica''''', the '''Panama rubber tree''', is a tree native to the [[Tropics|tropical]] areas of [[Mexico]], [[Central America]], and northern [[South America]].<ref>{{GRIN | accessdate=2009-10-16}}</ref> It was the principal source of [[latex]] among the [[Mesoamerica]]n peoples in [[pre-Columbian]] times. The latex gathered from ''Castilla elastica'' was converted into usable [[rubber]] by mixing the latex with the juice of the [[morning glory]] species ''[[Ipomoea alba]]'' which, conveniently, is typically found in the wild as a [[vine]] climbing ''Castilla elastica''. The rubber produced by this method found several uses, including most notably, the manufacture of balls for the [[Mesoamerican ballgame]] ''ōllamaliztli''.
The [[Aztec]] ([[Nahuatl]]) word for rubber was ''ulli / olli'', from which their word for the ballgame derived), and also their name for the ancient people they associated with the origin of the ballgame, the [[Olmec]]s (''olmeca'': "rubber people"). The Nahuatl word for the tree of ''Castilla elastica'' is '''''olicuáhuitl''''';<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.conabio.gob.mx/conocimiento/info_especies/arboles/doctos/48-morac2m.pdf |title=''Castilla elastica'' |publisher=Comisión Nacional para el Conocimiento y Uso de la Biodiversidad}}</ref> in [[Spanish (language)|Spanish]] it is known as '''palo de hule'''.
==Subspecies== *''Castilla elastica'' ssp. ''costaricana'' <small>(Liebm.) C.C.Berg</small> *''Castilla elastica'' ssp. ''elastica''
== Vernacular names == Caucho, castilloa rubber.
==See also== *[[Guayule]] - another source of latex utilized by the pre-Columbian Mesoamericans *[[Para rubber tree]] - the main source of modern commercial natural latex
