{{ Infobox scientist | name = Emma Rush | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = Australian | ethnicity = | fields = | workplaces = [[Charles Sturt University Faculty of Arts]], School of Humanities and Social Sciences | alma_mater = Department of Philosophy/Centre for Applied Philosophy and Public Ethics, [[University of Melbourne]] | thesis_title = Consume with care: ethics, economics and industrialised world over-consumption | thesis_url = https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/224910719 | thesis_year = 2004 | doctoral_advisor = | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = Reports for [[The Australia Institute]] | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | influences = | influenced = | awards = | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | footnotes = | website = {{official|https://arts-ed.csu.edu.au/schools/humss/staff/profiles/lecturers/emma-rush}} }}
'''Emma Rush''' is a lecturer in philosophy and ethics at [[Charles Sturt University Faculty of Arts]], School of Humanities and Social Sciences, notable for her work on sexualisation of children.<ref name=Charles_Sturt>{{cite web|title=Dr Emma Rush|url=http://www.csu.edu.au/faculty/arts/humss/staff/profiles/philosophy/emma-rush|publisher=Charles Sturt University, School of Humanities and Social Sciences|accessdate=20 August 2017}}</ref>
In 2006, Rush worked on a series of reports for [[The Australia Institute]]. Two of the reports which she co-authored<ref name=Corporate>{{cite book|last1=Rush|first1=Emma|last2=La Nauze|first2=Andrea|title=Corporate paedophilia: the sexualisation of children in Australia (discussion paper number 90)|date=2006|publisher=The Australian Institute|location=Canberra|oclc=156752334 |ISSN=1322-5421 }} [http://www.tai.org.au/documents/downloads/DP90.pdf Pdf version.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180516001004/http://www.tai.org.au/documents/downloads/DP90.pdf |date=16 May 2018 }}</ref><ref name=Letting>{{cite book|last1=Rush|first1=Emma|last2=La Nauze|first2=Andrea|title=Letting children be children: stopping the sexualisation of children in Australia (discussion paper number 93)|date=2006|publisher=The Australian Institute|location=Canberra|oclc=225513585 |ISSN=1322-5421 }} [http://www.parliament.qld.gov.au/Documents/TableOffice/TabledPapers/2014/5414T4837.pdf Pdf version.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140717202746/http://www.parliament.qld.gov.au/Documents/TableOffice/TabledPapers/2014/5414T4837.pdf |date=17 July 2014 }}</ref> led to a senate inquiry into the sexualisation of children.<ref name=CCYP>{{cite book|title=Senate inquiry into the sexualisation of children in the contemporary media environment|date=2008|publisher=The Commission for Children and Young People (CCYP), State Government Victoria|location=[[Victoria, Australia]]|url=http://www.ccyp.vic.gov.au/childsafetycommissioner/downloads/submission_senateinquiry_media_sexn_of_kids.pdf|access-date=15 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130510203521/http://www.ccyp.vic.gov.au/childsafetycommissioner/downloads/submission_senateinquiry_media_sexn_of_kids.pdf|archive-date=10 May 2013|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
Rush has also been consulted by the media, including Australia's [[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] and ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]''.
== Research == Rush's main areas of research are: [[environmental ethics]] and [[Ethics|ethics in public life]], particularly, [[Sexualization|sexualisation of children]] and the [[Day care|corporatisation of child care]].<ref name=Charles_Sturt />
== Media == Rush has acted as a media consultant over issues relating to sexualisation, advertising and pornography debates by [[ABC Radio and Regional Content|ABC Radio, Australia]],<ref>{{cite AV media|people=Scott Stephens (presenter), Dr. Emma Rush (guest) |title=RN Drive|trans-title=[http://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/drive/can-an-anti-abortion-activist-be-called-a-feminist3f/3816694 Can an anti-abortion activist be called a feminist?] |medium=Radio show|publisher=[[ABC Radio and Regional Content|ABC]]|time=6.45pm |location=Australia|date=7 February 2012}}</ref> [[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News, Australia]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rush|first1=Emma|title=Media must do better on porn debate|url=http://www.abc.net.au/religion/articles/2012/02/01/3420737.htm|accessdate=15 July 2014|publisher=ABC News|date=1 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140719043801/http://www.abc.net.au/religion/articles/2012/02/01/3420737.htm|archive-date=19 July 2014|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'',<ref name=Tween>{{cite news|last1=Rush|first1=Emma|last2=Norma|first2=Caroline|title=Sexed up tween advertising shows fashion needs to grow up|url=http://www.smh.com.au/opinion/society-and-culture/sexed-up-tween-advertising-shows-fashion-needs-to-grow-up-20120215-1t788.html|accessdate=12 July 2014|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|date=16 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104180610/http://www.smh.com.au/opinion/society-and-culture/sexed-up-tween-advertising-shows-fashion-needs-to-grow-up-20120215-1t788.html|archive-date=4 November 2012|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rush|first1=Emma|title=Girls on film: could new regulations stop the sexualisation of children?|url=http://theconversation.com/girls-on-film-could-new-regulations-stop-the-sexualisation-of-children-6762|accessdate=15 July 2014|publisher=The Conversation|date=23 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140719172918/http://theconversation.com/girls-on-film-could-new-regulations-stop-the-sexualisation-of-children-6762|archive-date=19 July 2014|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and [[Melinda Tankard Reist]]'s website.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rush|first1=Emma|title=Teens have hearts, not just bodies|url=http://melindatankardreist.com/2012/02/teens-have-hearts-not-just-bodies/|publisher=Melinda Tankard Reist|accessdate=15 July 2014|date=8 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140720233755/http://melindatankardreist.com/2012/02/teens-have-hearts-not-just-bodies/|archive-date=20 July 2014|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
