[[Category:Reproduction]]


{{animal-anatomy-stub}}

{{short description|a linear ridge on the Indian Ocean floor near the 90th meridian}} [[File:NinetyEastRidge.jpg|right|thumb|240px|The Ninety East Ridge at the centre of the picture and the [[Chagos-Laccadive Ridge]] on the upper left side]] The '''Ninety East Ridge''' (also rendered as '''Ninetyeast Ridge''', '''90E Ridge''' or '''90°E Ridge''') is a linear structure on the [[Indian Ocean]] floor named for its near-parallel strike along the [[90th meridian east|90th meridian]] at the center of the [[Eastern Hemisphere]]. It is approximately {{convert|5000|km|mi}} in length and can be traced topographically from the [[Bay of Bengal]] southward towards the [[Southeast Indian Ridge]] (SEIR), though the feature continues to the north where it is hidden beneath the sediments of the [[Bengal Fan]]. The ridge extends between latitudes [[33rd parallel south|33°S]] and [[17th parallel north|17°N]] and has an average width of 200&nbsp;km.<ref name=Ramana>{{cite journal |last=Ramana |first=M.V. |author2=T. Ramprasad |author3=M. Desa |author4=V. Subrahmanyam |title=Integrated geophysical studies over the 85°E ridge - Evaluation and interpretation |journal=Visakha Science Journal |year=2000 |volume=4 |issue=1 |pages=45–56 |url=http://drs.nio.org/drs/handle/2264/428}}</ref>
The ridge divides the Indian Ocean into the West and East Indian Ocean. The northeastern side is named the [[Wharton Basin]] and ceases at the western end of the [[Diamantina Fracture Zone]] which passes to the east and almost to the Australian continent.<ref name="Stow">Stow, D. A. V. (2006) ''Oceans : an illustrated reference'' Chicago : University of Chicago Press, {{ISBN|0-226-77664-6}} - page 127 for map of Indian Ocean and ridges</ref>
The ridge is primarily composed of [[Tholeiitic basalt|Ocean Island Tholeiites]] (OIT), a subset of [[basalt]] which increase in age from approximately 43.2 ± 0.5 Ma in the south to 81.8 ± 2.6 Ma in the north<ref name="Weis">{{cite journal |last=Weis |first=D. |title=The Influence of Mantle Plumes in Generation of Indian Oceanic Crust |journal=Geophysical Monograph |volume=70 |issue= |pages=57–89 |year=1993 |doi=10.1029/gm070p0057|display-authors=etal |bibcode=1992GMS....70...57W}}</ref> though a more recent analysis using modern [[Argon–argon dating|Ar–Ar techniques]] is currently pending{{Update after|2018|7|21}} publication. This age progression has led geologists to theorize that a [[hotspot (geology)|hotspot]] in the [[Mantle (geology)|mantle]] beneath the [[Indo-Australian Plate]] created the ridge as the plate has moved northward in the late [[Mesozoic]] and [[Cenozoic]]. This theory is supported by a detailed analysis of the chemistry of the [[Kerguelen Plateau]] and [[Rajmahal Traps]], which together, geologists believe, represent the [[flood basalt]]s erupted at the initiation of volcanism at the [[Kerguelen hotspot]] which was then sheared in two as the Indian subcontinent moved northward.<ref name="Weis" /> However, the existence of so-called deep [[Mantle (geology)|mantle]] [[hotspot (geology)|hotspots]] is currently a topic of debate in the geologic community, with a few geochemists favoring an alternative hypothesis which postulates a much shallower origin for [[hotspot (geology)|hotspot]] volcanism.<ref name="King">{{cite journal |last=King |first=S. D. |first2=D. L. |last2=Anderson |year=1995 |title=An Alternative Mechanism of Flood Basalt Formation |journal=Earth and Planetary Science Letters |volume=136 |issue=3–4 |pages=269–279 |doi=10.1016/0012-821X(95)00205-Q |bibcode = 1995E&PSL.136..269K }}</ref>
The ridge has been surveyed several times in the past, including several times by the [[Deep Sea Drilling Program]] (DSDP). In 2007, the [[RV Roger Revelle]] collected bathymetric, magnetic and seismic data together with dredge samples from nine sites along the ridge as part of an [[Integrated Ocean Drilling Program]] (IODP) site survey intended to examine the hotspot hypothesis for the ridge.<ref name=KNOX06RR>{{cite web|title=Seismic Project Information KNOX06RR Ninetyeast Ridge IODP Survey|url=http://www-udc.ig.utexas.edu/sdc/cruise.php?cruiseIn=knox06rr|publisher=The University of Texas at Austin}}</ref>
It had been assumed that the India and Australia are on a single tectonic plate for at least the last 32 million years. However, considering the high level of large earthquakes in the Ninety East Ridge area and the evidence of deformation in the central Indian Ocean, it is more appropriate to consider the deformed region in the central Indian Ocean as a broad plate boundary zone separating the Indian Plate and the Australian Plate.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Stein | first1 = S. | last2 = Okal | first2 = W. A. | title = Seismicity and Tectonics of the Ninetyeast Ridge Area: Evidence for Internal Deformation of the Indian Plate | year = 1974 | journal = Journal of Geophysical Research | volume = 83 | issue = B5 | url = http://www.earth.northwestern.edu/individ/emile/PDF/EAO016.pdf | access-date = 23 May 2015 | doi=10.1029/jb083ib05p02233 | bibcode=1978JGR....83.2233S | pages=2233}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Van Orman | first1 = J. | last2 = Cochran | first2 = J. R. | last3 = Weissel | first3 = J. K. | last4 = Jestin | first4 = F. | title = Distribution of shortening between the Indian and Australian plates in the central Indian Ocean | year = 1995 | journal = Earth and Planetary Science Letters | volume = 133 | pages = 35–46 | url = http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0012821X9500061G | access-date = 23 May 2015 | doi=10.1016/0012-821x(95)00061-g | bibcode=1995E&PSL.133...35V}}</ref>
